es including Gothic, crime, humour and romance, Marsh produced stories about shape-shifting monsters, morally dubious heroes, lip-reading female detectives and objects that come to life. However, while Marsh’s work appealed to a public greedy for sensationalist fiction, both the cultural elite of the day and twentieth-century literary critics looked askance at his popular middlebrow fiction. In the wake of the recent rediscovery of Marsh’s fiction, this essay collection builds on burgeoning scholarly interest in the author. Marsh emerges here as a fascinating writer who helped shape the genres of popular fiction and whose stories offer surprising responses to issues of criminality, gender and empire in this period of cultural transition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish fictionxHistoryy19th century. 0aEnglish fictionxHistoryy20th century. 0aPopular literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aPopular literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 4aGothic 2020. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aBernard Heldmann.  aCrime.  aCritical theory.  aFin de siècle.  aGender.  aGothic.  aLiterary culture.  aMiddlebrow.  aPopular fiction.  aRichard Marsh.1 aAllsop, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartlett, Mackenzie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBulfin, Ailise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreeman, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHultgren, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHöglund, Johan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMargree, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.